                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d572">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Japanese Chargé</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1905-04-18">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 18, 1905</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Hioki</hi>: I have to-day received a cablegram
                    from Mr. Meyer, our ambassador at St. Petersburg, who says he is in receipt of a
                    detailed report from Mr. Smith, the United States vice-consul at Moscow, who has
                    lately paid a visit to the Japanese prisoners.</p>
                <p>Major-General Lanouschinski, who is in charge of all the Japanese prisoners in
                    Russia, informed Consul Smith that an allowance of 30 kopecks is now being
                    received by each Japanese private soldier. Mr. Smith states also that he was
                    present at the midday meal with the prisoners and he himself ate the food
                    supplied, which he states was excellent.</p>
                <p>I transmit this for your information, and such consideration as you may choose to
                    give it.</p>
                <p>Very sincerely, yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis B. Loomis.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
